Kubernetes service helps to enable pod communication both internal and external communication.

** There are four types of services
  1. NodePort             ----- External communication
  2. LoadBalancer         ----- External communication
  
  3. ClusterIP            ----- Internal communication
  4. Headless             ----- Internal communication

****************************************************************************************

1. NodePort:-  A NodePort service is one of the basic ways to expose a Kubernetes application outside the cluster.

How NodePort works=
    1. You create a Service with type NodePort.
    
    2. Kubernetes assigns a port from a fixed range, usually 30000 to 32767.
    
    3. Any request sent to
       NodeIP:NodePort
       reaches the Service.
    
    4. The Service forwards the request to one of the matching Pods.


Example service YAML file
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: nginx-nodeport
spec:
  type: NodePort
  selector:
    app: nginx
  ports:
    - port: 80          # Service port
      targetPort: 80   # Pod port
      nodePort: 30007  # Exposed port on each node


SVC applies all nodes levels by default not stick single node
ex. If I create node port service same node port enabled for all nodes
***********************************************************************************************************

Practicle
1. Create Eks and node group
2. create 1 ec2 instance and connect it and install kubernetes and connfigure aws credentials
3. create NodePort.yml file
4. Run file = kubectl apply -f NodePort.yml
5. kubectl get pods -o wide  = note internal ip 
6. kubectl get nodes -o wide = take external ip of noted internal ip and search <ip>:<nodeport- mentioned in yml file>
7. kubectl get svc = describes the services
8. kubectl describe svc <service-name>



2. LoadBalancer =
    A LoadBalancer Service in Kubernetes is the clean way to expose your application outside the cluster using a cloud provider’s native load balancer. 
    Since you’re on AWS, this usually means an Application Load Balancer (ALB) or Network Load Balancer (NLB).

Run LoadBalancer.yml file 
kubectl get svc
you will see load balancer take that and check web site is running or not.



